function maxTasks(tasks, workers, pills, strength) {
  tasks.sort((a, b) => a - b);
  workers.sort((a, b) => a - b);

  let cnt = 0;
  let i = 0;
  for (let j = 0; j < pills; ++j) {
    while (i < tasks.length && tasks[i] > workers[j] + strength) {
      ++i;
    }
    if (i < tasks.length) {
      ++cnt;
      ++i;
    }
  }

  for (i = 0, j = pills; i < tasks.length && j < workers.length; ++i) {
    if (tasks[i] <= workers[j]) {
      ++cnt;
      ++j;
    }
  }

  return cnt;
}
```


    First, we sort both the tasks and the workers lists. This will simplify our assignments later.

We then count the number of tasks that will be completed given the available pills. Start with the lowest task and check if a worker with a pill can complete the task. If a worker with a pill can complete the task, we add 1 to our task counter and move to the next task. We do this for all pills as long as there are remaining tasks.

Finally, we check the remaining tasks and workers without pills to see if they can complete any tasks. We start with the lowest task and try to match it to a worker without a pill. If a worker can complete the task, we increment our task counter and move to the next task.

We return the total number of tasks that can be completed.

